{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"As a particle physicist, I study the elementary particles"},{"time":4000,"text":"and how they interact on the most fundamental level."},{"time":7000,"text":"For most of my research career, I've been using accelerators,"},{"time":10000,"text":"such as the electron accelerator at Stanford University, just up the road,"},{"time":13000,"text":"to study things on the smallest scale."},{"time":16000,"text":"But more recently, I've been turning my attention"},{"time":18000,"text":"to the universe on the largest scale."},{"time":21000,"text":"Because, as I'll explain to you,"},{"time":23000,"text":"the questions on the smallest and the largest scale are actually very connected."},{"time":27000,"text":"So I'm going to tell you about our twenty-first-century view of the universe,"},{"time":32000,"text":"what it's made of and what the big questions in the physical sciences are --"},{"time":35000,"text":"at least some of the big questions."}]},{"cues":[{"time":37000,"text":"So, recently, we have realized"},{"time":40000,"text":"that the ordinary matter in the universe --"},{"time":42000,"text":"and by ordinary matter, I mean you, me,"},{"time":45000,"text":"the planets, the stars, the galaxies --"},{"time":47000,"text":"the ordinary matter makes up only a few percent"},{"time":50000,"text":"of the content of the universe."},{"time":52000,"text":"Almost a quarter, or approximately a quarter"},{"time":55000,"text":"of the matter in the universe, is stuff that's invisible."},{"time":58000,"text":"By invisible, I mean it doesn't absorb in the electromagnetic spectrum."},{"time":62000,"text":"It doesn't emit in the electromagnetic spectrum. It doesn't reflect."},{"time":65000,"text":"It doesn't interact with the electromagnetic spectrum,"},{"time":67000,"text":"which is what we use to detect things."},{"time":69000,"text":"It doesn't interact at all. So how do we know it's there?"},{"time":72000,"text":"We know it's there by its gravitational effects."},{"time":74000,"text":"In fact, this dark matter dominates"},{"time":77000,"text":"the gravitational effects in the universe on a large scale,"},{"time":80000,"text":"and I'll be telling you about the evidence for that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":82000,"text":"What about the rest of the pie?"},{"time":84000,"text":"The rest of the pie is a very mysterious substance called dark energy."},{"time":88000,"text":"More about that later, OK."},{"time":90000,"text":"So for now, let's turn to the evidence for dark matter."},{"time":93000,"text":"In these galaxies, especially in a spiral galaxy like this,"},{"time":96000,"text":"most of the mass of the stars is concentrated in the middle of the galaxy."},{"time":101000,"text":"This huge mass of all these stars keeps stars in circular orbits in the galaxy."},{"time":108000,"text":"So we have these stars going around in circles like this."},{"time":111000,"text":"As you can imagine, even if you know physics, this should be intuitive, OK --"},{"time":115000,"text":"that stars that are closer to the mass in the middle will be rotating at a higher speed"},{"time":121000,"text":"than those that are further out here, OK."}]},{"cues":[{"time":124000,"text":"So what you would expect is that if you measured the orbital speed of the stars,"},{"time":129000,"text":"that they should be slower on the edges than on the inside."},{"time":133000,"text":"In other words, if we measured speed as a function of distance --"},{"time":135000,"text":"this is the only time I'm going to show a graph, OK --"},{"time":137000,"text":"we would expect that it goes down as the distance increases"},{"time":141000,"text":"from the center of the galaxy."},{"time":143000,"text":"When those measurements are made,"},{"time":144000,"text":"instead what we find is that the speed is basically constant,"},{"time":147000,"text":"as a function of distance."},{"time":149000,"text":"If it's constant, that means that the stars out here"},{"time":152000,"text":"are feeling the gravitational effects of matter that we do not see."},{"time":156000,"text":"In fact, this galaxy and every other galaxy"},{"time":159000,"text":"appears to be embedded in a cloud of this invisible dark matter."},{"time":164000,"text":"And this cloud of matter is much more spherical than the galaxy themselves,"},{"time":168000,"text":"and it extends over a much wider range than the galaxy."},{"time":172000,"text":"So we see the galaxy and fixate on that, but it's actually a cloud of dark matter"},{"time":176000,"text":"that's dominating the structure and the dynamics of this galaxy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":181000,"text":"Galaxies themselves are not strewn randomly in space;"},{"time":184000,"text":"they tend to cluster."},{"time":186000,"text":"And this is an example of a very, actually, famous cluster, the Coma cluster."},{"time":189000,"text":"And there are thousands of galaxies in this cluster."},{"time":192000,"text":"They're the white, fuzzy, elliptical things here."},{"time":195000,"text":"So these galaxy clusters -- we take a snapshot now,"},{"time":198000,"text":"we take a snapshot in a decade, it'll look identical."},{"time":201000,"text":"But these galaxies are actually moving at extremely high speeds."},{"time":205000,"text":"They're moving around in this gravitational potential well of this cluster, OK."},{"time":210000,"text":"So all of these galaxies are moving."},{"time":212000,"text":"We can measure the speeds of these galaxies, their orbital velocities,"},{"time":216000,"text":"and figure out how much mass is in this cluster."}]},{"cues":[{"time":218000,"text":"And again, what we find is that there is much more mass there"},{"time":222000,"text":"than can be accounted for by the galaxies that we see."},{"time":226000,"text":"Or if we look in other parts of the electromagnetic spectrum,"},{"time":228000,"text":"we see that there's a lot of gas in this cluster, as well."},{"time":231000,"text":"But that cannot account for the mass either."},{"time":233000,"text":"In fact, there appears to be about ten times as much mass here"},{"time":236000,"text":"in the form of this invisible or dark matter"},{"time":239000,"text":"as there is in the ordinary matter, OK."},{"time":243000,"text":"It would be nice if we could see this dark matter a little bit more directly."},{"time":247000,"text":"I'm just putting this big, blue blob on there, OK,"},{"time":249000,"text":"to try to remind you that it's there."},{"time":251000,"text":"Can we see it more visually? Yes, we can."}]},{"cues":[{"time":254000,"text":"And so let me lead you through how we can do this."},{"time":256000,"text":"So here's an observer:"},{"time":258000,"text":"it could be an eye; it could be a telescope."},{"time":260000,"text":"And suppose there's a galaxy out here in the universe."},{"time":262000,"text":"How do we see that galaxy?"},{"time":264000,"text":"A ray of light leaves the galaxy and travels through the universe"},{"time":267000,"text":"for perhaps billions of years"},{"time":269000,"text":"before it enters the telescope or your eye."},{"time":272000,"text":"Now, how do we deduce where the galaxy is?"},{"time":275000,"text":"Well, we deduce it by the direction that the ray is traveling"},{"time":278000,"text":"as it enters our eye, right?"},{"time":280000,"text":"We say, the ray of light came this way;"},{"time":282000,"text":"the galaxy must be there, OK."},{"time":284000,"text":"Now, suppose I put in the middle a cluster of galaxies --"},{"time":288000,"text":"and don't forget the dark matter, OK."},{"time":290000,"text":"Now, if we consider a different ray of light, one going off like this,"},{"time":294000,"text":"we now need to take into account"},{"time":296000,"text":"what Einstein predicted when he developed general relativity."},{"time":299000,"text":"And that was that the gravitational field, due to mass,"},{"time":303000,"text":"will deflect not only the trajectory of particles,"},{"time":306000,"text":"but will deflect light itself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":309000,"text":"So this light ray will not continue in a straight line,"},{"time":312000,"text":"but would rather bend and could end up going into our eye."},{"time":316000,"text":"Where will this observer see the galaxy?"},{"time":319000,"text":"You can respond. Up, right?"},{"time":323000,"text":"We extrapolate backwards and say the galaxy is up here."},{"time":326000,"text":"Is there any other ray of light"},{"time":327000,"text":"that could make into the observer's eye from that galaxy?"},{"time":330000,"text":"Yes, great. I see people going down like this."},{"time":333000,"text":"So a ray of light could go down, be bent"},{"time":335000,"text":"up into the observer's eye,"},{"time":337000,"text":"and the observer sees a ray of light here."}]},{"cues":[{"time":339000,"text":"Now, take into account the fact that we live in"},{"time":341000,"text":"a three-dimensional universe, OK,"},{"time":343000,"text":"a three-dimensional space."},{"time":345000,"text":"Are there any other rays of light that could make it into the eye?"},{"time":348000,"text":"Yes! The rays would lie on a -- I'd like to see -- yeah, on a cone."},{"time":354000,"text":"So there's a whole ray of light -- rays of light on a cone --"},{"time":356000,"text":"that will all be bent by that cluster"},{"time":358000,"text":"and make it into the observer's eye."},{"time":361000,"text":"If there is a cone of light coming into my eye, what do I see?"},{"time":366000,"text":"A circle, a ring. It's called an Einstein ring. Einstein predicted that, OK."},{"time":370000,"text":"Now, it will only be a perfect ring if the source, the deflector"},{"time":375000,"text":"and the eyeball, in this case, are all in a perfectly straight line."},{"time":380000,"text":"If they're slightly skewed, we'll see a different image."}]},{"cues":[{"time":383000,"text":"Now, you can do an experiment tonight over the reception, OK,"},{"time":386000,"text":"to figure out what that image will look like."},{"time":389000,"text":"Because it turns out that there is a kind of lens that we can devise,"},{"time":393000,"text":"that has the right shape to produce this kind of effect."},{"time":396000,"text":"We call this gravitational lensing."},{"time":398000,"text":"And so, this is your instrument, OK."},{"time":401000,"text":"(Laughter)."},{"time":402000,"text":"But ignore the top part."},{"time":405000,"text":"It's the base that I want you to concentrate, OK."},{"time":408000,"text":"So, actually, at home, whenever we break a wineglass,"},{"time":410000,"text":"I save the bottom, take it over to the machine shop."},{"time":412000,"text":"We shave it off, and I have a little gravitational lens, OK."},{"time":416000,"text":"So it's got the right shape to produce the lensing."},{"time":418000,"text":"And so the next thing you need to do in your experiment"},{"time":420000,"text":"is grab a napkin. I grabbed a piece of graph paper -- I'm a physicist. (Laughter)"},{"time":424000,"text":"So, a napkin. Draw a little model galaxy in the middle."},{"time":428000,"text":"And now put the lens over the galaxy,"},{"time":431000,"text":"and what you'll find is that you'll see a ring, an Einstein ring."},{"time":434000,"text":"Now, move the base off to the side,"},{"time":437000,"text":"and the ring will split up into arcs, OK."},{"time":440000,"text":"And you can put it on top of any image."},{"time":442000,"text":"On the graph paper, you can see"},{"time":443000,"text":"how all the lines on the graph paper have been distorted."},{"time":445000,"text":"And again, this is a kind of an accurate model"},{"time":448000,"text":"of what happens with the gravitational lensing."}]},{"cues":[{"time":450000,"text":"OK, so the question is: do we see this in the sky?"},{"time":454000,"text":"Do we see arcs in the sky when we look at, say, a cluster of galaxies?"},{"time":458000,"text":"And the answer is yes."},{"time":460000,"text":"And so, here's an image from the Hubble Space Telescope."},{"time":462000,"text":"Many of the images you are seeing"},{"time":464000,"text":"are earlier from the Hubble Space Telescope."},{"time":466000,"text":"Well, first of all, for the golden shape galaxies --"},{"time":468000,"text":"those are the galaxies in the cluster."},{"time":471000,"text":"They're the ones that are embedded in that sea of dark matter"},{"time":475000,"text":"that are causing the bending of the light"},{"time":477000,"text":"to cause these optical illusions, or mirages, practically,"},{"time":480000,"text":"of the background galaxies."},{"time":482000,"text":"So the streaks that you see, all these streaks,"},{"time":485000,"text":"are actually distorted images of galaxies that are much further away."}]},{"cues":[{"time":489000,"text":"So what we can do, then, is based on how much distortion"},{"time":492000,"text":"we see in those images, we can calculate how much mass"},{"time":496000,"text":"there must be in this cluster."},{"time":498000,"text":"And it's an enormous amount of mass."},{"time":500000,"text":"And also, you can tell by eye, by looking at this,"},{"time":502000,"text":"that these arcs are not centered on individual galaxies."},{"time":506000,"text":"They are centered on some more spread out structure,"},{"time":510000,"text":"and that is the dark matter"},{"time":514000,"text":"in which the cluster is embedded, OK."},{"time":517000,"text":"So this is the closest you can get to kind of seeing"},{"time":519000,"text":"at least the effects of the dark matter with your naked eye."}]},{"cues":[{"time":522000,"text":"OK, so, a quick review then, to see that you're following."},{"time":525000,"text":"So the evidence that we have"},{"time":527000,"text":"that a quarter of the universe is dark matter --"},{"time":529000,"text":"this gravitationally attracting stuff --"},{"time":531000,"text":"is that galaxies, the speed with which stars orbiting galaxies"},{"time":535000,"text":"is much too large; it must be embedded in dark matter."},{"time":538000,"text":"The speed with which galaxies within clusters are orbiting is much too large;"},{"time":542000,"text":"it must be embedded in dark matter."},{"time":544000,"text":"And we see these gravitational lensing effects, these distortions"},{"time":548000,"text":"that say that, again, clusters are embedded in dark matter."}]},{"cues":[{"time":551000,"text":"OK. So now, let's turn to dark energy."},{"time":555000,"text":"So to understand the evidence for dark energy, we need to discuss something"},{"time":558000,"text":"that Stephen Hawking referred to in the previous session."},{"time":562000,"text":"And that is the fact that space itself is expanding."},{"time":566000,"text":"So if we imagine a section of our infinite universe --"},{"time":571000,"text":"and so I've put down four spiral galaxies, OK --"},{"time":574000,"text":"and imagine that you put down a set of tape measures,"},{"time":578000,"text":"so every line on here corresponds to a tape measure,"},{"time":580000,"text":"horizontal or vertical, for measuring where things are."},{"time":584000,"text":"If you could do this, what you would find"},{"time":586000,"text":"that with each passing day, each passing year,"},{"time":589000,"text":"each passing billions of years, OK,"},{"time":592000,"text":"the distance between galaxies is getting greater."},{"time":595000,"text":"And it's not because galaxies are moving"},{"time":596000,"text":"away from each other through space."},{"time":599000,"text":"They're not necessarily moving through space."},{"time":601000,"text":"They're moving away from each other"},{"time":603000,"text":"because space itself is getting bigger, OK."},{"time":606000,"text":"That's what the expansion of the universe or space means."},{"time":610000,"text":"So they're moving further apart."}]},{"cues":[{"time":612000,"text":"Now, what Stephen Hawking mentioned, as well,"},{"time":616000,"text":"is that after the Big Bang, space expanded at a very rapid rate."},{"time":622000,"text":"But because gravitationally attracting matter"},{"time":626000,"text":"is embedded in this space,"},{"time":628000,"text":"it tends to slow down the expansion of the space, OK."},{"time":631000,"text":"So the expansion slows down with time."},{"time":634000,"text":"So, in the last century, OK, people debated"},{"time":638000,"text":"about whether this expansion of space would continue forever;"},{"time":643000,"text":"whether it would slow down, you know,"},{"time":645000,"text":"will be slowing down, but continue forever;"},{"time":647000,"text":"slow down and stop, asymptotically stop;"},{"time":652000,"text":"or slow down, stop, and then reverse, so it starts to contract again."},{"time":657000,"text":"So a little over a decade ago,"},{"time":659000,"text":"two groups of physicists and astronomers"},{"time":664000,"text":"set out to measure the rate at which"},{"time":666000,"text":"the expansion of space was slowing down, OK."},{"time":670000,"text":"By how much less is it expanding today,"},{"time":672000,"text":"compared to, say, a couple of billion years ago?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":675000,"text":"The startling answer to this question, OK, from these experiments,"},{"time":680000,"text":"was that space is expanding at a faster rate today"},{"time":684000,"text":"than it was a few billion years ago, OK."},{"time":687000,"text":"So the expansion of space is actually speeding up."},{"time":690000,"text":"This was a completely surprising result."},{"time":693000,"text":"There is no persuasive theoretical argument for why this should happen, OK."},{"time":699000,"text":"No one was predicting ahead of time this is what's going to be found."},{"time":702000,"text":"It was the opposite of what was expected."},{"time":704000,"text":"So we need something to be able to explain that."},{"time":707000,"text":"Now it turns out, in the mathematics,"},{"time":709000,"text":"you can put it in as a term that's an energy,"},{"time":713000,"text":"but it's a completely different type of energy"},{"time":714000,"text":"from anything we've ever seen before."},{"time":716000,"text":"We call it dark energy,"},{"time":718000,"text":"and it has this effect of causing space to expand."},{"time":721000,"text":"But we don't have a good motivation"},{"time":723000,"text":"for putting it in there at this point, OK."},{"time":725000,"text":"So it's really unexplained as to why we need to put it in."}]},{"cues":[{"time":728000,"text":"Now, so at this point, then, what I want to really emphasize to you,"},{"time":732000,"text":"is that, first of all, dark matter and dark energy"},{"time":734000,"text":"are completely different things, OK."},{"time":736000,"text":"There are really two mysteries out there as to what makes up most of the universe,"},{"time":740000,"text":"and they have very different effects."},{"time":743000,"text":"Dark matter, because it gravitationally attracts,"},{"time":746000,"text":"it tends to encourage the growth of structure, OK."},{"time":750000,"text":"So clusters of galaxies will tend to form,"},{"time":753000,"text":"because of all this gravitational attraction."},{"time":755000,"text":"Dark energy, on the other hand,"},{"time":757000,"text":"is putting more and more space between the galaxies,"},{"time":761000,"text":"makes it, the gravitational attraction between them decrease,"},{"time":764000,"text":"and so it impedes the growth of structure."},{"time":767000,"text":"So by looking at things like clusters of galaxies,"},{"time":770000,"text":"and how they -- their number density,"},{"time":774000,"text":"how many there are as a function of time --"},{"time":776000,"text":"we can learn about how dark matter and dark energy"},{"time":780000,"text":"compete against each other in structure forming."}]},{"cues":[{"time":783000,"text":"In terms of dark matter, I said that we don't have any,"},{"time":786000,"text":"you know, really persuasive argument for dark energy."},{"time":790000,"text":"Do we have anything for dark matter? And the answer is yes."},{"time":793000,"text":"We have well-motivated candidates for the dark matter."},{"time":796000,"text":"Now, what do I mean by well motivated?"},{"time":799000,"text":"I mean that we have mathematically consistent theories"},{"time":804000,"text":"that were actually introduced"},{"time":806000,"text":"to explain a completely different phenomenon, OK,"},{"time":809000,"text":"things that I haven't even talked about,"},{"time":811000,"text":"that each predict the existence"},{"time":814000,"text":"of a very weakly interacting, new particle."}]},{"cues":[{"time":817000,"text":"So, this is exactly what you want in physics:"},{"time":819000,"text":"where a prediction comes out of a mathematically consistent theory"},{"time":823000,"text":"that was actually developed for something else."},{"time":825000,"text":"But we don't know if either of those"},{"time":828000,"text":"are actually the dark matter candidate, OK."},{"time":831000,"text":"One or both, who knows? Or it could be something completely different."},{"time":834000,"text":"Now, we look for these dark matter particles"},{"time":836000,"text":"because, after all, they are here in the room, OK,"},{"time":839000,"text":"and they didn't come in the door."},{"time":840000,"text":"They just pass through anything."},{"time":842000,"text":"They can come through the building, through the Earth --"},{"time":844000,"text":"they're so non-interacting."}]},{"cues":[{"time":846000,"text":"So one way to look for them is to build detectors"},{"time":849000,"text":"that are extremely sensitive to a dark matter particle coming through and bumping it."},{"time":853000,"text":"So a crystal that will ring if that happens."},{"time":856000,"text":"So one of my colleagues up the road and his collaborators"},{"time":858000,"text":"have built such a detector."},{"time":860000,"text":"And they've put it deep down in an iron mine in Minnesota,"},{"time":863000,"text":"OK, deep under the ground, and in fact, in the last couple of days"},{"time":866000,"text":"announced the most sensitive results so far."},{"time":869000,"text":"They haven't seen anything, OK, but it puts limits on what the mass"},{"time":872000,"text":"and the interaction strength of these dark matter particles are."},{"time":875000,"text":"There's going to be a satellite telescope launched later this year"},{"time":879000,"text":"and it will look towards the middle of the galaxy,"},{"time":882000,"text":"to see if we can see dark matter particles annihilating"},{"time":884000,"text":"and producing gamma rays that could be detected with this."},{"time":888000,"text":"The Large Hadron Collider, a particle physics accelerator,"},{"time":891000,"text":"that we'll be turning on later this year."},{"time":894000,"text":"It is possible that dark matter particles might be produced"},{"time":897000,"text":"at the Large Hadron Collider."}]},{"cues":[{"time":899000,"text":"Now, because they are so non-interactive,"},{"time":900000,"text":"they will actually escape the detector,"},{"time":903000,"text":"so their signature will be missing energy, OK."},{"time":906000,"text":"Now, unfortunately, there is a lot of new physics"},{"time":909000,"text":"whose signature could be missing energy,"},{"time":911000,"text":"so it will be hard to tell the difference."},{"time":913000,"text":"And finally, for future endeavors, there are telescopes being designed"},{"time":918000,"text":"specifically to address the questions of dark matter and dark energy --"},{"time":922000,"text":"ground-based telescopes, and there are three space-based telescopes"},{"time":925000,"text":"that are in competition right now"},{"time":927000,"text":"to be launched to investigate dark matter and dark energy."},{"time":930000,"text":"So in terms of the big questions:"},{"time":932000,"text":"what is dark matter? What is dark energy?"},{"time":934000,"text":"The big questions facing physics."},{"time":936000,"text":"And I'm sure you have lots of questions,"},{"time":939000,"text":"which I very much look forward to addressing"},{"time":941000,"text":"over the next 72 hours, while I'm here. Thank you."},{"time":943000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}